{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01K5N1QHY859Na5CgoJ3Z4jb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the LEVEL-DEFS and KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Does the failure only appear when multiple modules interact? The behavior tests whether the AI vision model correctly classifies an image as explicit AND the downstream system holds it for review. The \"flagged and held\" part involves the pipeline: vision model → flagging logic → hold decision. But the core question is whether an image containing explicit content gets correctly identified by the AI model. \n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess required.\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the AI vision model to always return \"explicit\" would only test the routing logic, not whether the model actually detects explicit content in real images.\n- LLM-DEP: The behavior fundamentally depends on the AI vision model correctly classifying the image—a stub can't verify this correctness.\n- Minimum level: **Agentic** — requires the real AI vision model to accurately identify explicit content.\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obf**\n\nuscation techniques.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: The core challenge here is whether the AI text model can handle obfuscation like letter substitution and unicode lookalikes.\n- LLM-DEP: A deterministic stub wouldn't test the model's actual ability to detect obfuscated hate speech—correctness depends on the real model's capabilities.\n- Minimum level: **Agentic** — requires the real AI text model to correctly classify obfuscated hate speech.\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the decision logic—if both checks pass, the system should publish, not hold or drop.\n- REAL-INFRA: No actual OS or network infrastructure needed.\n- LLM-DEP: The AI models themselves don't need to be real here; I can stub both as \"pass\" and verify the routing logic works correctly.\n- MOCK-HIDE: With both checks stubbed to return \"pass,\" any failure would surface in the decision logic itself.\n- Minimum level: **Integration** — wires the two check modules and publish decision together using stubs for the models, testing where check results route to publish versus hold.\n\nActually, this could be Unit-level if the decision logic is a single function that takes both check results and routes accordingly—testing \"pass, pass\" → publish would be straightforward. But the question is whether the behavior spans multiple modules or lives in one.\n\nFor Behavior 4, this is clearly a performance test requiring the full pipeline to run end-to-end, so I need real infrastructure and actual model execution to measure latency. Performance under real conditions. If we use stubs for the AI models, we can test pipeline latency but that doesn't reflect real model call latency. However, the behavior says \"within 5 seconds\" — this is a system-level performance requirement.\n- LLM-DEP: The latency depends on real AI model calls. With stubs, you'd get near-zero latency and the test would always pass, hiding real latency issues.\n- Wait — does the behavior require real AI models to test latency? If the concern is that the pipeline orchestration is slow (not the AI model calls), Integration would work. But if the AI model calls are the bottleneck (which they typically are), you'd need Agentic to catch real failures.\n- Actually, the behavior is about the complete pipeline latency including real AI model calls. A stub that returns instantly would always pass the 5-second threshold. The real failure would be the AI models taking too long.\n\nThis requires running the full pipeline with multiple agentic steps in sequence: image check, text check, then publish decision. That's at least two AI model calls happening one after another, so the minimum level is Workflow — you need those real model calls to make the latency test meaningful.\n\nNow looking at the vision model unavailability scenario. The key failure mode here is when the vision model goes down, the system should queue posts for retry instead of auto-approving them. This is about how the system handles that specific dependency failure.\n\nI can simulate the vision model being unavailable with a stub that throws an exception — that's a deterministic error condition, not something that requires real network behavior. The test would verify that when the vision model call fails, the error handling logic correctly routes the post to the retry queue rather than auto-approving it. This is an integration-level concern because it's testing the wiring between the vision model call, the error handler, and the queue mechanism.\n\nFor the consistency behavior with borderline images, I'm checking whether this is about caching or deduplication logic.  If the system caches results for repeated submissions within a short window, that's an integration test with a stubbed AI model. But if the behavior is actually about the AI model itself being consistent on borderline cases, that requires the real model since borderline images are inherently non-deterministic — the model might classify them differently on different runs. The behavior description suggests it's about the AI model's consistency on borderline cases, which would push this toward an agentic test level. tests whether the system handles this by ensuring consistency (likely through caching or deduplication). \n\nThe key insight: \"borderline\" + \"consistent\" + \"short window\" suggests this is about whether the system implements some form of consistency guarantee (caching, locking, deduplication) for cases where the AI model might be non-deterministic.\n\nIf we test this with a real AI model, a borderline image might genuinely get different responses on different calls, which is the failure we're trying to catch. Without a real model, a deterministic stub would always return the same result, potentially hiding consistency issues.\n\nBut also — the system might have a caching mechanism. If it does, even a non-deterministic model would be consistent for cached results. The test would verify that the caching mechanism works correctly.\n\nSo the real question is whether this test needs a stub that returns different results to verify the cache works, or whether it needs a real AI model to catch genuine non-determinism on borderline cases. A non-deterministic stub would test the caching layer, but the behavior seems specifically concerned with how the AI model itself behaves on edge cases — which points toward needing real model behavior to properly validate the system's consistency guarantees. Now I'm writing out the test descriptions and justifications for each behavior. For the explicit content detection, I need to explain why a real AI vision model is essential—stubs would only validate the routing logic, not whether the model actually catches explicit material. Similarly, obfuscated hate speech requires the real text model since the whole point is that these techniques are designed to evade AI detection, so testing against a stub would miss the actual failure mode.\n\nFor the clean post behavior, though, this is different—the critical failure is in the routing and publishing logic itself, not in model accuracy. Stubs returning \"pass\" verdicts are sufficient here because I'm testing whether the system correctly publishes when both checks pass, not whether the models themselves work correctly.\n\nFor the latency test, I need to use real AI model calls since stubs would mask the actual performance bottleneck. The pipeline involves sequential agentic steps that only reveal timing issues under real conditions, so this has to run against the live models to be meaningful.\n\nNow looking at the vision model unavailability scenario...\n\nwhen the vision model fails, the post should queue for retry rather than getting auto-approved. I can stub the vision model to throw an exception and verify the retry queue receives it without triggering a publish call.\n\nFor borderline images, the challenge is that real AI models introduce non-determinism—the same image might score differently across repeated calls. A deterministic stub would hide this variability, so I need to test against the actual model to catch inconsistent moderation decisions.\n\nNow I'm working through the probability distribution for each test level, starting with how likely each behavior is to be caught at Unit, Integration, System, Agentic, and Workflow levels. Now I'm working through the probability distributions for the remaining behaviors, checking that error handling and retry logic would primarily be integration tests, while image generation with AI introduces more agentic complexity and non-determinism. Let me verify all these weightings sum correctly. Now I'm verifying that each test description aligns with its minimum required level—the vision and text model tests are agentic, the stub-based one is integration, the real model calls are workflow-level, the exception handling with retry logic is integration, and the threshold-adjacent vision model test is agentic. Everything checks out.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9927,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9927},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7b84885b-f274-4612-8df1-fa440f54e335","uuid":"2178236e-1f5e-402f-be62-88f92f083e8e"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01K5N1QHY859Na5CgoJ3Z4jb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FqAby8ypntFbmHzzNSSxBY","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is whether the AI vision model correctly classifies explicit content — not whether the downstream routing logic works. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the vision model to return 'explicit' always passes and tests only the routing, hiding real model classification failures. LLM-DEP: The model may fail to detect explicit content in some images, mislabel borderline cases, or miss adversarial inputs. Only a real model call can expose these. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because no real OS/network behavior is under test; the failure is in model output quality, not infrastructure.","test_description":"Submit a curated set of images with known-explicit content directly to the moderation pipeline backed by the real AI vision model. Assert that every image is assigned a 'held for review' status and none reach the published state.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is entirely within the AI text model's ability to handle adversarial inputs. Letter substitution and unicode lookalikes are evasion techniques designed specifically to fool classifiers. MOCK-HIDE: A deterministic stub would always return 'flagged' for the test inputs, completely hiding whether the real model handles obfuscation. LLM-DEP: Classification accuracy on obfuscated inputs varies with the real model — different prompting strategies, model versions, or tokenization edge cases cause real failures that only appear with the live model. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because the failure is not at a module boundary; it is in the model's internal handling of specific token patterns.","test_description":"Submit text posts containing hate speech encoded with several distinct obfuscation patterns (l33t-speak substitution, unicode homoglyphs, mixed-script insertion) to the moderation pipeline using the real AI text model. Assert each post is flagged, none are published.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the conditional routing logic after both check modules produce 'pass' verdicts. A bug here (e.g., incorrect boolean logic, missing publish call, default-to-hold fallback) only appears when the check results propagate across module boundaries to the publish decision. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing both check modules to return 'pass' is correct here — the real failure is not in model accuracy but in whether the orchestrator correctly invokes the publisher given two passing verdicts. REAL-INFRA: No OS or real network behavior is required. LLM-DEP: No — this tests deterministic routing logic, not model quality. REJECTION-GATE: Unit rejected because 'silently dropped' implies the failure is in the actual publish invocation, requiring the publisher module to be wired in.","test_description":"Wire together the image check module, text check module, and publisher module with stubs configured to return 'pass' for both checks. Submit a clean post and assert the publisher receives a 'publish' call, the post status is 'published', and no hold or drop action is triggered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing either AI model produces near-zero latency, making the test pass trivially and hiding real latency failures caused by model response time, serialization overhead, or queuing under load. REAL-INFRA: Wall-clock latency of real AI API calls is the dominant variable; in-process fakes cannot reproduce this. LLM-DEP: Each model call introduces real, variable latency. MULTI-STEP: The pipeline involves two sequential agentic steps (real AI vision model call followed by real AI text model call) before the publish decision — exactly the Workflow pattern. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic rejected because the behavior explicitly spans two sequential AI calls; testing only one model call would not exercise the cumulative pipeline latency.","test_description":"Submit a post containing both image and text through the full live pipeline (real AI vision and text model endpoints). Record wall-clock time from submission receipt to final publish/hold decision. Assert total elapsed time is under 5 seconds. Repeat across a representative sample to account for model latency variance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.64}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is at the module boundary between the vision model client's error path and the retry queue: a bug here means the error handler auto-approves or drops the post instead of enqueuing it. This only appears when the error-handling code interacts with the queue module. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the vision model client to raise an unavailability exception is the correct approach — the real failure is not in network behavior but in how the error path routes to the queue. REAL-INFRA: No real AI model, real network, or real OS behavior is needed; a controllable stub that raises on call is sufficient. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because the failure does not depend on real network timeout behavior — a synchronous in-process exception from the stub correctly reproduces the unavailability condition.","test_description":"Configure the vision model client stub to raise an unavailability exception on every call. Submit an image post and assert: (1) the post appears in the retry queue with its original payload, (2) no publish call is made, and (3) no auto-approval status is set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The behavior explicitly targets 'borderline' images — inputs near the model's classification threshold where real AI models produce non-deterministic outputs across repeated calls. A deterministic stub always returns the same result, trivially passing the consistency check and hiding any real inconsistency. The only way to expose this failure is to send the same borderline image to the real model multiple times and observe divergence. MOCK-HIDE: A stub cannot reproduce the model's actual score distribution for a borderline input; it hides the problem entirely. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because the consistency issue does not originate at a module boundary; it originates in the live model's scoring variance for edge-case inputs. If the system uses caching, the Agentic test also validates that the cache correctly absorbs model non-determinism.","test_description":"Identify an image empirically confirmed to score near the classification threshold of the real AI vision model. Submit it at least 5 times in rapid succession through the live moderation pipeline. Assert all returned decisions are identical (all 'held' or all 'published') with no divergence across submissions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9927,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9927},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7b84885b-f274-4612-8df1-fa440f54e335","uuid":"5db660d4-c3ca-4b91-93f3-fcecce00a34f"}
